The first virtual provider will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced and our service providers offer practically the same services as their Western European partners.
Nevertheless, something is missing here for us - a virtual provider that forces classic providers to significant price decrease.
Maybe it will not be so for a long time.
On the Mobil.cz website we have repeatedly written that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This is also confirmed by the Czech Republic, which pointed out that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in other EU countries.
Following the European Commission’s latest step in regulating roaming fees, this may result in a controversial situation – SMS from abroad to some Czech mobile service providers will be cheaper than domestic.
How is it possible that the prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of a competition that really wants to go into struggle.
This may sound contradictory because we have three mobile networks and our penetration is above 100%.
Mobile service providers, on the contrary, are pleased to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvořák, the chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office, has repeatedly stated that there is no room for new service providers in the Czech Republic.
Per it is true that a classic provider with its own network probably no longer has too many chances (although it is likely to have a difficult time to find frequency).
However, there is another option - the virtual provider.
The entry of virtual service providers to the mobile market led to a significant decline in prices, which the classic service providers had to respond to.
In the meantime, even before big fish entered the market, such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile in the UK, sounds similar to us were heard.
However, it has been proven that such providers have their place and can really be successful.
For example, we don’t have to go too far.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the Mobilking virtual service provider in Poland.
This service provider has achieved more than 100,000 customers in just a half year and has become the fifth largest service provider there.
Meanwhile, behind Mobilking is the Penta Financial Group, which in the Czech Republic is the owner of the U:fon.
The advantage of virtual providers is the possibility of focusing on a much closer target group.
For efficient operations, it requires much less customers than the traditional service provider.
It does not result in relatively high cost of construction, operating and maintenance of mobile networks.
Virtual providers in the world, therefore, usually appear to be low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which, however, are often compensated with less service.
For example, the UK Tesco Mobile offers at least 50 percent cheaper SMS messages than its competitors.
But, as the example of the Polish Mobilking shows, a very good pull can also be booked on a target group.
This service is specifically focused on men.
"Real men choose the Mobilking provider - who they like, who they can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobil Entertainment Company, which operates this virtual provider.
It’s hard to say if a similar idea in Poland can succeed in us.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický claims: “The Czech market is relatively small to the segment approach on which the majority of virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively satisfied with the supply of services.”
Mobile service providers are unlikely in the Czech Republic
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a kind of virtual provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about a successful expansion of this project, but negotiations in the Czech Republic don’t seem too hopeful.
The launch of Mobilking will rather take place in other countries in our region,” said Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for the Penta Financial Group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
It indirectly confirmed that the existing mobile service providers in the Czech Republic are not excessively sympathetic with this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do their best to ensure that there is no potential competition.
The GTS Novera group has long not hidden its interest in the launch of a virtual provider, which thus intends to take a further step to make Telefonica O2 a real competitor in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in providing our customers with not only wireless, but also mobile telecommunications services.
The more quickly, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile service providers.
Some of them have already succeeded in the negotiations,” says Pavel Kaidl, a spokesman for the group.
Maybe better times are coming.
Unformal information shows that the first virtual provider may be lucky until the end of the year.
However, his birth is still surrounded by a wall of unbeatable silence.
“At this point, we don’t think that a full-value virtual provider would have a place on the Czech market.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very special.
Until now, we have not been called by a single subject that offers a complex and serious project in this area,” said Vlastimil Sršeň from the Television 02 press class.
The specific situation of the Czech market is also referred to by other providers.
Martina Kemrová, spokeswoman for T-Mobile, expressly agrees with O2, adds: “We have not yet recorded any viable and bilateral profitable business project that could be further based on.”
And he added: "In the T-Mobile network, it is unlikely that any virtual provider will appear by the end of the year.
At this point, there should be a concrete agreement on our table, so that we can think in such a short term."
Vodafone is more concerned about compliance with its own 3G license requirements.
Miroslav Čepický adds: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, primarily in the field of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is what we think is the most expensive for our customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this field is partnering to build shared networks for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible offices - a crowd with service providers
The process of mobile service providers is easy to understand, the entry of a new service provider would result in increased competition, decreasing prices and thus decreasing their profits.
So why should we make it easier to enter such a competition?
When something is important to the providers, they are able to cooperate, it also witnesses the line around the birth of the U:fon.
The greatest pressure on ČTÚ was probably about the birth of the T-Mobile company’s U:fon.
This is confirmed by the publicly available information on the website.
But now the U:fon comes well as a reason why we do not allow the entrance of the virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová added: “The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been impacted by the entry of the fourth mobile service provider on the market.
Having regard to the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player’s entry into the market and its services would have high demands.”
However, having regard to this attitude of mobile service providers, the total disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is quite surprising.
Meanwhile, it’s not just the attitude of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately – unlike the UK and other developed countries – has no right to interfere with economic competition.
This is only the competition authority.
However, the office is characteristically concerned with the whole problem.
“Virtual service provider’s entry into the mobile market would be possible only after a contract between the mobile service provider and the virtual service provider was signed for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such agreement has been concluded, as the offer of potential stakeholders is likely not relevant to traditional service providers," said Kristián Chlapua, the Department of External Relations of the Economic Competition Office, in response to our question.
A statement from the representatives of the service providers will probably not surprise anyone.
However, from the office, which should represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, ensure that no one can recover from its market position, this is more than strange.
Specifically, if Kristián Chalupa adds: "In abroad, where virtual service providers normally operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the price of mobile phone services."
However, it is unlikely that the pressure towards the proper functioning of the market environment and the price decrease is not within the interests of the new OECD.
In this case, it is truly shocking that the perfect consistency from the reactions of the three mobile service providers.
The question of whether it is only a coincidence is almost self-understood.
As in charging stations, the exactly identical gasoline prices are only works of coincidence and harsh competition.
“The Office has not revealed signs of an anti-competitive proceedings in this case, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
No service provider has a leading position, i.e. it has no proportionally greater responsibility for its market performance.
The tools needed to open the mobile market for virtual service providers are likely to be missing by the telecommunications regulator,” Chalupa said.
The presentation of market leadership is one of the many points of dispute.
Of course, there is an analysis of relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, based on which telecommunications are the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
Of course, there is no Czech provider in such a market.
However, some legal experts also offer a different viewpoint - the creation of a virtual provider always requires the approval of the network operator.
And the mobile provider - relatively logically - has a monopoly on its own network.
Therefore, in a certain segment it is necessarily dominant.
But even if we would not accept this argument, it should be a minimum incentive for UOHS that three mobile service providers do seemingly similarly.
Meanwhile, the complaints of a number of stakeholders (including the already mentioned GTS Novera company) show that they are facing very similar obstacles during negotiations with all service providers.
The transfer of responsibility to ČTÚ is a relatively usual trick in telecommunications, with which the UOHS takes his hand away from the whole matter.
We have seen it in some similar situations.
Unfortunately, in the text of the newly adopted telecommunications law, the extension of the powers of ČTÚ in the field of economic competition in telecommunications was not achieved, although many experts hoped that the situation would improve.
The representatives of the new OHS should know this well, but they probably have other interests.
It works when no one is listening.
Meanwhile, it remains unnoticed the functioning of some kind of false-virtual providers, many of which are already operating in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies issuing their own mobile service pricing lists, which, however, are only partially public.
It is a multilevel marketing company.
Thus, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Pricing lists of these companies are usually only available to the selected.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts against the provider as a classic corporate customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a priority customer, you will receive special price offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile service providers prohibit similar pre-requisits.
“If there were cases we’re talking about, it could be a contract breach that we’d deal with and which could lead to the end of cooperation with that company,” Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this issue.
But it is quite unlikely that the news of such activity would not have reached the people responsible for the mobile service providers.
In particular, the three companies may be thousands of customers.
At the same time, no service provider will defend against such a procedure.
In fact, these companies have no negligible profits from their activities, and at the same time, unlike real virtual providers, they are not threatened by their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns of possible problems: "The law allows similar speculations, however, the services of these companies are used by only an overwhelming percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not listed in their name, so they cannot have it fully as the general customers of the mobile service providers.”
But this is exactly what I think should be strange at least.
In addition, another question is also raised to the U.S.
If mobile service providers are looking at a similar procedure, why do they prevent the birth of a virtual service provider?
It should be added that the UOHS has a relatively strong authority to reveal such activity, and if it does not want it, it does not have to be satisfied with the service providers' explanation that they did not think of anything like that and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we’re not the most expensive
As mentioned several times in the text, the entrance of virtual service providers to the mobile market has led to a noticeable decline in the prices of services.
Meanwhile, in virtually every country where virtual service providers were established, classical service providers tried to prevent their establishment more or less.
The arguments they used were practically the same - too small, too satisfied market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the developed countries, however, regulatory bodies have intervened in these moments, which in no way defended the interests of mobile service providers, but of their customers.
Then, even with formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual provider that others followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies give the whole case to each other.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that unclear competencies are good for them in these cases.
But don’t give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider will really appear soon, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If a service provider would allow the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, the UOHS may only find it difficult to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may not be more expensive than the rest of Europe.
