The rats also have emotions.
A rats or a mole escapes in the event of a danger. Does this mean he feels afraid?
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that animals also have emotions.
But how can we see if they feel the same when they behave like us?
For years, famous scientists have published their articles in the "Edge" online magazine.
In one of the series, SPIEGEL ONLINE looks at the answers to the question "What is real without proofing?"
I believe that animals have emotions and other state of consciousness without me or anyone else to be able to prove this so far. It is true that we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
In this case, however, we can at least hope that the basic configuration of every human brain is the same.
However, as we explore other species and get the questions of perception or consciousness in general, we get to a difficult ground because the hardware does not match.
When a rats are in danger, they do the same as many other animals: they make themselves dead, escape or attack.
People behave in a similar way, from which some researchers conclude to comparable subjective experiences.
I do not believe in this.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our own subjective experiences to animals.
Circuits related to human consciousness, on the one hand, almost always contain the lateral prefrontal brain cells (for its role in short-term memory and in execution/management functions).
This wide area is more advanced for humans than for other primates, and it seems to be completely missing for other living creatures.
At least from the aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal brain cavity, such as the consciousness of who we are, or with the ability to plan and make decisions, it is justified to assume that a person is different even from the other major creators.
Another dramatic peculiarity lies in the linguistic nature of man: Since a significant part of human experience is related to the language, it is often claimed that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals can be excluded.
However, even if consciousness was not dependent on the language, the language would surely influence it, so the animal consciousness, whatever nature it is, is likely to be very different from most of our state of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness can be for other animals.
If consciousness cannot be measured as an internal and subjective thing, and it cannot be analyzed on the basis of our own experience due to the special hardware, then its research will bring us to serious problems.
Most of my heads are about the content of conscious life, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that is likely to be more accessible to science.
The conscious processes of animals, regardless of their content, could be examined, and this is exactly what happens in the case of short-term memory experiments of the masterminders, especially in the example of visualization.
However, in this assumption studied by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, they rely more on the nerve connections of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both can be the same or not.
Interestingly, this assumption also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal brain cough in the formation of visualization.
What about these emotions?
I lead this back to the fact that an emotional system, like fear, is activated in the brain that is aware of its own activity.
What we call "fear" is, therefore, the mental state in which we are when the activity of the defensive system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies the work memory.
Thus, examining the emotions are closely linked to the areas of the cerebrospinal cavity that are characteristic of the main sensors and especially of man.
In addition to the linguistic nature, perception is divided into subtle degrees, because with the help of words and linguistics we are able to distinguish and categorize states, to describe them to others besides ourselves.
On the contrary, for example, Antonio Damasio is the opinion that emotions are derived from the simpler activities of the body perception areas of the cerebrospinal and cerebrospinal cord, as well as Jaak Pankseep, who, however, is more focused on the cerebrospinal cord.
Since this network has not changed much during human evolution, it can easily play a role in the emotions that encompass the species.
Clearly theoretically, I cannot deny this, but I consider it unproved.
Pankseep believes that what seems a fear for rats and humans is likely to be felt in both cases: How can we check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave the same way?
A puppy escapes when it comes to danger, is he also afraid?
In my opinion, just similar behavior does not prove the same experience yet.
Nevertheless, neurological comparisons help further: rats and humans have a brain like them, but sheep don’t have a brain.
Is the brain responsible for emotions?
And even if this could be proved to humans: how can we prove this in the case of rats?
I think rats and other mammals, but even cats (who knows?) have emotions.
I don’t know how to prove this.
And since their emotions are suspiciously fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circles and language), I’m looking for the emotional behavior of rats rather than the emotional emotions.
In any case, the progress in this area is imminent at the neural level, if the same is measured in rats and humans.
As with rats, I do not explore language and consciousness, I do not explore emotions, because I do not know whether they exist.
For others, this may seem to be a short-looking attitude, but I’m going forward rather than constantly striking to a wall.
I am a practical emotionalist.
