Returning drunk drivers will be required to install the "Alcolock"
The Ministry of Internal Affairs would require the driver to install a structure that would prevent the vehicle from starting if the driver is drunk or does not swallow into the structure.
The proposal was submitted in June and is currently being discussed by the Prosecutor's Office, according to which the experimental project will last for a year.
Since the project is aimed at bringing it back to the market, the driver will also have to take part in a repeated course on transportation education.
In addition to the General Prosecutor's Office for Traffic Safety, the General Directorate of Transportation (DGT) and the Institute of Automotive Safety Technology Foundation (FITSA) are also involved in the experiment.
According to statistics, 30-75% of those arrested several times because of drunk driving are sitting in the car again.
This will be prevented by Alcolock, as the system connected to the vehicle determines the alcohol level of the inflated air. If it is greater than permitted, or if the driver does not inflat in the device at all, the system does not allow the vehicle to start.
The cost of an instrument of more than 1000 euros will be charged by the infringer.
A 2007 study in the U.S. showed that vehicles equipped with such instruments could reduce the number of infringements by up to 65% in the first year after installation.
In Spain, the rule is estimated to save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure focuses on infringements for two reasons: on the one hand, it is easier to prevent them from becoming criminal.
On the other hand, it is easier to implement, as the legal reform is carried out in the usual manner, while the necessary criminal reform would require a basic law amendment.
The device is not yet available in any commercial form on the Spanish market, although in experimental mode it has already been installed in some industrial and public services vehicles.
The House of Representatives will vote tomorrow on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which, according to the French pattern, calls for the installation of the system in school buses.
