As you know, the national reserve of blood treated by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Supplier Service was infected with the acquired immunodeficiency symptoms (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
After the drama and the general devastation, the Canadian government launched an official investigation in February 1994 under the leadership of Judge Horace Krever, with the aim of revealing the circumstances that led to the tragedy and making proposals to avoid future similar cases.
While Krever judge was delayed by submitting his report, some provinces set up their own committee aimed at designing a new blood treatment system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this task.
According to the Gélineau and Krever reports, two blood supply services have been established in Canada: one is Héma-Quebec, which serves Quebec, and the other is the Canadian Blood Supply Company, which is responsible for all other provinces and the two territories.
“When Héma-Québec started its activity in 1998, just 38% of people had confidence in the blood supply system in Québec,” recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was desperate.
“In the coming years, however, the improvement of the safety of blood preparations and our work in the area have succeeded in regaining people’s confidence,” Decary proudly states that at the beginning of 2008, 94% of Quebec’s population considered Héma-Quebec reliable.
However, Dr. Decary doesn’t forget that “confidence is an extremely fragile thing.”
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the principle of caution.
During this period, a number of cases have been discovered in Europe when a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease infected people, says the doctor, who has managed the company since its founding in 1998.
"We didn't know if this disease spreads through blood.
Therefore, we rely on one of the most important recommendations in the Krever and Gélineau reports. According to this, if we are uncertain about this and there is a risk of developing a serious disease, then we need to take exclusive measures. In this case, it was about the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob, which causes a brain damage, which inevitably leads to death.
Therefore, in April 1999, we did not receive blood from people who have spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980.
And a few years ago, any doubt was found that the disease spread through the blood.
This case convinced us that it was reasonable to apply the principle of caution.”
This is a nucleic acid test (NAT), which is able to directly detect the virus in the blood of donors, rather than the antibodies that form against the virus, on which the previously used tests were built.
With the help of the NAT test, we could shorten the window period, which lasts from infection until we can detect the virus in the blood with the help of our technical tools, the specialist explains.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk of an unknown blood donor to infect the blood supply was significantly reduced and that this could not be detected.
These developments have significantly reduced the risk of the spread of AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, the risk of getting a person infected with HIV is 12 million per one.
In other words, this means that we should allocate 12 million blood clots until someone is infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes 400-500 thousand blood prescriptions each year, more than 24 years should take for such a case to occur and someone to get infected with HIV through a blood prescriptions.
I think today anyone can calmly accept or prescribe a blood transfusion in order to restore your health, says Héma-Québec's number one leader.
“The challenge of the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
We can never know what new pathogens will enter the system.
For it was only last year that the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, passed into the blood with insects.
That’s why we have to be constantly in the gap,” continued Dr. Décary, and then emphasized that in addition to the digestive reserves, Héma-Quebec needs to provide sufficient permanent reserves.
“As the population ages, the demand is increasing.
Since anti-cancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need red blood cells or blood plates to be replaced.
The ageing population also affects the blood donor stock, as the number of people in the network who are able to donate blood accounts for only 3% of the Quebec population.
However, any healthy person, at least 18 years of age, who meets the conditions of aptitude may donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
