In this fasting world today, one man has hardly an hour to go to give blood,” Francis Decary says.
Héma-Québec, which has an annual budget of $297 million, provides not only blood preparations, but also human tissues, such as bone transplants, heart keys, eye ball tissues and skin tissues, which are used almost exclusively for people with severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen, and then placed at Héma-Québec, which at the same time manages the only public stem cell bank in Québec.
A blood that is rich in stem cells can be obtained from the bladder, which is only treated as a medical waste, allowing the treatment of severe diseases (such as leukemia).
