Wall Street rescue action: Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush government and the Republican and Democratic leaders of Congress have finally reached an agreement on the economic rescue action, which is the biggest plan since the great world economic crisis in the 1930s.
The $700 billion plan, aimed at mitigating the financial crisis on Wall Street for months, is still to be approved by the two House of Congress.
The key points of the plan are: more effective monitoring of the implementation by the representatives; new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of the state funds provided; new provisions to maintain the number of houses booked due to the lack of payments; the right of insight into the payments to the managers of the undertakings assisted.
Henry Paulson, U.S. Secretary of Finance, Nancy Pelosi, President of the House of Representatives and Judd Gregg, the Republican representative participating in the talks yesterday, a few minutes before midnight, announced the good news after the two-day marathon talks ended.
“We’ve made great progress towards a solution that will work effectively on the markets,” said Henry Paulson, a representative for the Bush government.
“We did everything with the aim of saving the real economy and the American citizens from the current Wall Street crisis,” the Democrat said.
“The most important point is that if we don’t do this, the shock, chaos and confusion in the everyday lives of the Americans will be huge,” Judd Gregg said.
The negotiations have been accelerated in the last few hours, fearing that another failure would have a negative impact on the mood of investors.
The stock market had a deadline until opening this morning.
The two presidential candidates who came late to the talks showed themselves ready to reach a deal, but they said they were not happy that the situation was worsening to the end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama attributed to himself the extension of the agreement to elements such as provisions relating to the preservation of households or the payments to the leaders of companies assisted by the state.
“When we ask taxpayers to take some extraordinary actions because of the irresponsibility of other people, it’s not so pleasant.
These steps, however, are necessary,” he said in a US television show.
When his opponent, John McCain, was asked by another channel whether he would vote for the proposed plan, he replied, "I would like to know the details, but I hope that yes."
“What I’ve read in big lines, it’s already seen that it’s a thing that we all have to digest and through which we can move forward.
The possibility of not doing anything is simply unacceptable,” he said.
According to the $700 billion plan, taxpayers will buy from the money of suspicious claims from U.S. financial institutions, something risky, unsellable assets.
This first led to the collapse of risky real estate loans (secondary mortgage loans) and then spread to other (commercial) securities that incorporate credit relations, and eventually caused the freezing of liquid resources and the disintegration of banks and financial institutions.
The first draft agreement was defeated by a group of Republican members last week.
It seems that we’ve managed to get out of this trap since the Democrats agreed that certain “toxic” assets of companies in difficult situations would rather be provided by the government rather than purchased.
In order to ensure that all members of Congress are satisfied, the plan also includes a provision that requires that if the government has to bear the losses under the program for five years, it may impose new taxes to recover its resources.
As part of the new plan, a $250 billion deal will be paid first, followed by another $100 billion if the president considers it necessary.
The remaining $350 billion will be voted by Congress.
In exchange for the aid, Washington gains shares in the supported companies, through which it receives dividends from the profits and which it can sell after the crisis is relieved.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay the reservation of properties covering the mortgage loans covered in the plan. In addition, it will be able to set the maximum wage and final compensation to be paid to the managers of the undertakings affected by the crisis.
The proposals will be voted by the House of Representatives today and the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite their efforts, however, it is still uncertain that the plan will be approved.
There were repeated statements against the plan among both Republicans and Democrats.
“It is clear that Washington will not hear your voice,” Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House’s financial committee, said in a statement.
“We have serious financial problems.
Yes, there are solutions.
But there is no one that will benefit taxpayers.”
Brad Sherman, a democratic representative leading a small congressional group called a "skeptic group", shows things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred outstanding economists, including three Nobel prize winners, have written to us to ask Congress not to rush and to thoroughly examine which way they choose,” Sherman said.
In Europe, at the same time, it was again understood that this is a global crisis.
After a crisis meeting, the three Benelux states announced that they would state a part of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion U.S. dollars).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French BNP Paribas announced that it would not buy its competitor on the edge of bankruptcy after losing €2 million ($2.9 billion) as a result of the U.S. secondary mortgage crisis.
With 85,000 employees, Fortis is one of the 20 largest banks in Europe and one of the 10 largest insurance companies.
“It’s not a throw of money,” Dutch finance minister Wouter Bos said.
In return, we have the right to vote and influence in the bank.
This is exactly what depositors and households are appreciating now that the situation promises uncertain.”
Meanwhile, on the outskirts of La Manche, the British government seems to be preparing to nationalize a new bank that is overwhelmed by the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over the total of Bradford and Bringley bank’s ongoing loans, of which real estate loans amount to £41 billion ($75,5 billion).
The Spanish Santander bank announced yesterday that it will buy the British bank’s subsidiaries and customer stocks.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank after Northern Rock to be nationalized by the British government since the beginning of the crisis.
