Psychology of Excession: Why Do We Spend More Money?
At auctions, customers tend to spend more money, overestimate the goods.
The neurological-economic foundations of this known - and apparently irrational - behavior were discovered by Neurologists and economists at the University of New York.
According to a study published in the journal Science, people don’t want to undermine a type of competition like eBay auction, so they prefer to pay too high prices.
The research attempted to map the nervous scheme of this "playing" with the help of experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers lottoed, the other group participated in a player auction while using the method of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) examined the active brain areas of the experimental people.
In both games the participants were able to win money, but during the auction game - in which an essential element is the other party's overlifting - the striatum, under-brain complex began to work intensely when the game was lost.
This area of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the rise of the price can be explained by avoiding the intense reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the research group’s economists also conducted a financial monitoring investigation.
In this, three groups tendered against a partner under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed about the real value of the product and they made their bets.
Another group also promised that if they win out of the game, they will get another $15 in reward.
The third group, however, received just $15 before the auction, but the group members lost this money in the event of a losing auction.
Therefore, the difference between the two groups was only that they emphasized the victory for one and the loss for the other.
However, demonstrating the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the team playing against losses were willing to get higher rates than the control and the "winning" group.
"These findings cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
For so far, they have only explained the phenomena experienced at the auction with the joy of victory and the avoidance of risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped solve the contradiction between these two theories by now getting a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, professor at the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to go to a doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary, chronic liver disease is one of the leading causes of death.
There are hundreds of thousands of people infected with hepatitis here, but only seven thousand are treated, which is the reason: patients often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is the collection name of infectious liver products caused by various viruses.
In their symptoms there are many similarities, characteristic of hepatitis and yellowness, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are different from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the pathogen, are spread in two main forms: hepatitis A and E through the nutritional channel (e.g. infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body vessels (cranberry, vaginal vessels, saliva).
Travellers must be vaccinated against the A and B viruses, and there is no vaccine against the C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected food, generally accompanied by illness, weakness, abdominal complaint, nausea.
After these, it develops yellowness visible on the skin and the white of the eye, the outlet is bright, the urine becomes dark, healing can take two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people worldwide die in the most severe form of the disease, hepatitis B caused by liver cancer and liver sulfur.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only every ten infected people get medication treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can also lead to liver swelling, liver cancer.
Most infected people don’t even know about their disease, because the pathogen underlyingly destroys the liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear only after 20-30 years.
So then it is very important for early prevention, to perform regular screening tests.
In three groups, this disease is much more than the average: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug consumers and tattooed people.
The number of people infected with chronic hepatitis C in the world is now 200 million.
Since the disease can already be detected by a routine laboratory examination, when any symptoms of unknown origin are detected, it is advisable to consult a home doctor.
In time recognizing the disease can be healed, the virus can be removed from the body, thus eliminating the infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is the World Hepatitis Day, which was celebrated for the first time in 2004 by organizations that represent patients around the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to the chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early detection of the disease.
