To copy the complex eye function, engineers went to the idea of a laser distance meter.
It identifies the obstacles within a distance of 2 meters in a 180-degree view space before BR23C, calculates their distance, and sends a signal to the microprocessor on board, which is immediately translated into an operation to avoid collision.
During the breakdown of the second, the obstacle is detected, and then the car robot follows the movements of the uterus, immediately changing direction by turning its wheels to the extent necessary to avoid collision.
Unlike any current system, this avoidance maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive way.
"If this wasn't the case, the car-robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car-robot project.
